# Lines matching any regex below are exempt from git-secrets prohibited-pattern
# detection. Patterns are intentionally tight: they whitelist blog content
# (URLs, tutorial file paths, intentionally-published public keys / test API
# keys) without weakening detection of real AWS keys, GitHub tokens, etc.

# --- Markdown links and bare URLs in posts ---
\]\(https?://
\]\(http://
<https?://[^>]+>
^[[:space:]]*-?[[:space:]]*<?https?://
^[[:space:]]*\([0-9]+\)[[:space:]].+https?://
# Inline URLs inside text (e.g., "see https://...")
[[:space:]]https?://[^[:space:]]

# --- File paths in tutorial / shell output (>= 2 path segments) ---
/Users/[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+/[a-zA-Z0-9._/-]
/home/[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+/[a-zA-Z0-9._/-]

# --- Public asymmetric keys (educational content, not private material) ---
# Note: git-secrets word-splits multi-word prohibited patterns, so we avoid
# any literal substrings that could collide with those split tokens.
B[E]GIN PUBLIC
E[N]D PUBLIC

# --- OAuth 2.0 PKCE example values in security explainers ---
code_challenge=[A-Za-z0-9_-]+
code_verifier=[A-Za-z0-9_-]+

# --- Placeholder API keys in code samples (always truncated with `...`) ---
sk-[a-z]+-?[A-Za-z0-9]*\.\.\.
"sk-or-

# --- Subresource Integrity hashes used in HTML examples ---
sha512-[A-Za-z0-9+/=]+

# --- Publicly-published test API keys (the post text calls them out as test) ---
# Bracketed [s] keeps the literal off the 40-char [0-9a-zA-Z/+] AWS pattern.
[s]AJGq9JH193KiwnF947v74KnDYkO7z634LWQQfPY
